  "prompt": "How often do US inmates use smuggled cell phones in jail?",
  "response": "The use of smuggled cell phones in US jails is a notable issue, although exact statistics can be difficult to ascertain due to the illicit nature of the activity. Surveys and investigations have indicated that cell phone smuggling is relatively common in many correctional facilities. For instance, reports from various state prison systems reveal thousands of confiscations annually.\n\nSmuggled phones are used by inmates for a variety of purposes, including maintaining unauthorized communication with the outside world, coordinating illegal activities, and even conducting scams. The problem is pervasive enough that many prisons have implemented measures such as cell phone signal jamming technology, thorough searches, and the use of K-9 units trained to detect electronics.\n\nWhile there is significant variation between facilities in terms of the frequency of smuggling and detection, the issue remains a substantial concern for prison officials and law enforcement agencies nationwide.",
